 as conscious beings and examines the thorny scientific, philosophical, and ethical questions it raises. Once we accept that animals dream, we incur a host of moral obligations and have no choice but to rethink our views about who animals are and the interior lives they lead.A mesmerizing journey into the otherworldly domain of nonhuman consciousness, When Animals Dream carries profound implications for contemporary debates about animal cognition, animal ethics, and animal rights, challenging us to regard animals as beings who matter, and for whom things matter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnimal rightsxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aConsciousness in animals. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aAbductive reasoning.  aAffair.  aAlgorithm.  aAmerican Psychological Association.  aAmmunition.  aAmygdala.  aAnimal cognition.  aAnimal consciousness.  aAugustine of Hippo.  aBDSM.  aBehavior.  aBessel van der Kolk.  aBody schema.  aBoris Cyrulnik.  aBrainstem.  aChimpanzee.  aConcept learning.  aConsciousness.  aDelusion.  aDream world (plot device).  aEdmund Husserl.  aElaboration.  aEmpathy.  aEpilogue.  aExplanation.  aFacial muscles.  aFeeling.  aHallucination.  aHeat exhaustion.  aHuman science.  aImagination.  aInstance (computer science).  aIntentionality.  aIsolation tank.  aJean-Paul Sartre.  aJohn Searle.  aLucid dream.  aMental representation.  aMetacognition.  aMorality.  aNatural science.  aNed Block.  aNeuron.  aPhenomenology (psychology).  aPhenomenon.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophy of mind.  aPhilosophy of science.  aPhilosophy.  aPhysical property.  aPosterior cingulate.  aPosttraumatic stress disorder.  aPrima facie.  aProverb.  aPsychiatry.  aPyramidal cell.  aQualia.  aRapi